<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ880701-0059 </DOCNO><HL> Tenneco Gets Navy Contract For $2.95 Billion </HL><SO> </SO><CO> TGT TXT GD FMC UTX GQ RTN XON GM GMH BA IBM HRS MD GE </CO><IN> ARO </IN><G> DEF </G><DATELINE> WASHINGTON  </DATELINE><TEXT>   Newport News Shipbuilding andamp; Dry Dock Co., a unit of Tenneco Inc., received a $2.95 billion Navy contract for construction of two aircraft carriers.    Funding for these nuclear-powered carriers was provided in the budget for the fiscal year that began last Oct. 1. Newport News Shipbuilding, the sole producer of these carriers, will perform the work in Newport News, Va. Completion is scheduled for June 1998.    In other contracts yesterday, Textron Lycoming, a unit of Textron Inc., received Army jobs totaling $37 million for M-1 tank-engine support services and parts.    Units of General Dynamics Corp. were given contracts totaling $375 million for construction of an attack submarine for the Navy F-16 aircraft avionics maintenance equipment and logistics services for the Air Force, and M-1 tank production improvements for the Army.    FMC Corp. won a $282.4 million Army contract for production of armored vehicles.    Pratt andamp; Whitney Co., a unit of United Technologies Corp., received a $265.5 million Air Force contract for F-100 aircraft engine improvements.    Grumman Corp. was awarded Navy contracts totaling $206.2 million for A-6E and E-2C aircraft production and F-14 aircraft improvements.    Raytheon Co. got a $166.8 million Air Force contract for ballistic-missile early warning system improvement in the United Kingdom.    Exxon Co. U.S.A., a unit of Exxon Corp., received Air Force contracts totaling $55.4 million for jet fuel.    Hughes Aircraft Co., a unit of General Motors Corp., got a $29.4 million Army contract for the position-location reporting system.    Boeing Co. was issued a $25.6 million Air Force contract for missile security improvements.    International Business Machines Corp. got a $23.6 million Air Force contract for MC-130H aircraft radar-test equipment.    Harris Corp. was given an $18.9 million Army contract for satellite communications terminals.    Kurz andamp; Root Co. was issued a $14.3 million Army contract for electrical generators.    Airtacs Corp. received a $13.9 million Air Force contract for air conditioners.    Units of McDonnell Douglas Corp. won Air Force contracts totaling $12.7 million for aircraft ejection-seat modifications and computer software services.    Units of General Electric Co. were issued Air Force contracts totaling $12 million for aircraft gun parts and aircraft engine parts.    Space Data Corp. won a $10.5 million Air Force contract for launch vehicle modifications.    (Revised WSJ July 6, 1988)</TEXT></DOC>